ape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cumbre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Caliste, Francois, Lucien.","Altered form of German   Kamper  .","French: metonymic occupational name denoting someone who worked in the private quarters of his master, rather than the public halls of the manor, from <i>c(h)ambre</i> ‘room’, or a habitational name from Le Cambre or La Cambre, the names of a few places in the north of France. Compare   Delcambre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kamper","meanings":["German (Westphalia) and Dutch: topographic name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of   Kamp   1.","German: northern variant of <b>Kämpfer</b> (see   Kampfer  )."]},{"name":"Delcambre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Patrice, Gaston, Jacques, Minos.","French (mainly Nord): habitational name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, denoting someone from Le Cambre or La Cambre, the names of a few places in the north of France. Compare   Cambre  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":51,"year":"1215","julia